<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="26" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="26">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="26">
As already pointed out by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hita, Garcia F" journalOrPublisher="European Journal of Taxonomy" pageId="10" pageNumber="31" pagination="1 - 31" title="Taxonomy of the ant genus Nesomyrmex Wheeler (Formicidae, Myrmicinae) in the Afrotropical region, with a review of current species groups and description of a new species of the N. angulatus group from Mozambique." url="http://dx.doi.org/10.5852/ejt.2017.258" volume="258" year="2017">Hita Garcia et al. (2017)</bibRefCitation>
, this species has the widest distribution of any species of the 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. angulatus" pageId="5" pageNumber="26" rank="species" species="angulatus">N. angulatus</taxonomicName>
group, and is certainly the most widespread 
<taxonomicName authority="Wheeler, 1910" authorityName="Wheeler" authorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nesomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nesomyrmex" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Nesomyrmex</taxonomicName>
species worldwide. 
<taxonomicName authority="Wheeler, 1910" authorityName="Wheeler" authorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nesomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nesomyrmex angulatus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angulatus">Nesomyrmex angulatus</taxonomicName>
has been reported from most African countries, as well as on the Arabian Peninsula and most of the Malagasy Region. The species seems to prefer comparatively arid environments and is predominantly found in cavities of dead wood, trunk of trees, lower vegetation and rarely on the ground (
<bibRefCitation author="Bolton, B" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) Entomology" pageId="9" pageNumber="30" pagination="245 - 307" title="A revision of six minor genera of Myrmicinae (Hymenoptera: Formicidae) in the Ethiopian zoogeographical region." volume="43" year="1982">Bolton 1982</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Mbanyana, N" journalOrPublisher="African Natural History" pageId="11" pageNumber="32" pagination="35 - 55" title="Review of the ant genus Nesomyrmex (Hymenoptera: Formicidae: Myrmicinae) in southern Africa." volume="4" year="2008">Mbanyana and Robertson 2008</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="26" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="26">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="26">
This species exhibits remarkable variability throughout its distributional range, most notably in the shape of the petiolar node (
<bibRefCitation author="Bolton, B" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) Entomology" pageId="9" pageNumber="30" pagination="245 - 307" title="A revision of six minor genera of Myrmicinae (Hymenoptera: Formicidae) in the Ethiopian zoogeographical region." volume="43" year="1982">Bolton 1982</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Hita, Garcia F" journalOrPublisher="European Journal of Taxonomy" pageId="10" pageNumber="31" pagination="1 - 31" title="Taxonomy of the ant genus Nesomyrmex Wheeler (Formicidae, Myrmicinae) in the Afrotropical region, with a review of current species groups and description of a new species of the N. angulatus group from Mozambique." url="http://dx.doi.org/10.5852/ejt.2017.258" volume="258" year="2017">Hita Garcia et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
), but it is also relatively variable in body size and eye size. It is likely that the material currently understood to be 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. angulatus" pageId="5" pageNumber="26" rank="species" species="angulatus">N. angulatus</taxonomicName>
is actually a complex of cryptic species. However, in order to examine this question in detail it would be necessary to gather substantial material from throughout its whole distribution range from numerous museum collections. Despite that this is a highly desirable undertaking; it is outside the scope of the current study that focuses on the Arabian fauna only.
</paragraph>
